This component captures what method used in Attribution models.
For instance, in Verified, it captures how verification is achieved (verbal, written, telephone, etc.).

A reference range for the specific instance after lookup from, say, a reference range table given specific criteria. Note that this reference range is not definitional in nature but rather refers to the reference range considered for the given observation for a subject.
Indicates whether the given range is normal, critically high, ...

Asserted clinical justification to perform or not perform an act such as a diagnostic test, a medication treatment, or a procedure.
The justification can be specified as a code or as a clinical statement, e.g., code for diabetes (ICD-9-CM 250.0) or a Condition occurrence statement (with diabetes code) documented elsewhere in a patient's record.
A code representing the justification. Typically, the code is for a condition that is suspected or is observed in a patient.

The StatementContext class aligns with the SNOMED Situations with Explicit Context and provides the context for the topic of a clinical statement. Note that the action context provides the expressivity required to specify that an act was not done or a finding was observed to be absent. By default, the negation applies to the conjunction of the stated attribute in the instance.
The SNOMED 'Context value' code that most closely aligns with the contextual intent of the clinical statement.
A clinical procedure perfored on a subject, most often a patient.
Priority assigned to a procedure.
Anatomical location of the procedure.
The technique used to reach the site of the procedure. Approaches may be through the skin or mucous membrane, through an orifice or external.
Action being performed to accomplish the procedure.
Code for device associated with the procedure.
Device associated with the procedure.
The route used to access the site of a procedure. It is used to distinguish open, closed, and percutaneous procedures.

Records clinically significant observations confirmed or discovered during the procedure or surgery. For example, "Necrotic left ovarian cyst was discovered and removed." - ONC S&I Clinical Element Data Dictionary (CEDD), March 2012.
Materials placed during the procedure including stents, tubes, and drains.
Materials placed during the procedure including stents, tubes, and drains.
The energy used to execute the procedure.
Substance used to execute the action of a procedure.
Tissues, objects, or samples taken from the patient during the procedure including biopsies, aspiration fluid, or other samples sent for pathological analysis.

The ActionContext class aligns with the SNOMED Situations with Explicit Context and provides the context for the topic of a clinical statement. For instance, a statement about a procedure may specify that the procedure has been proposed, ordered, planned, performed or possibly not performed. Note that the action context provides the expressivity required to specify that an act was not done. By default, the negation applies to the conjunction of the stated attribute in the instance.
Reason or justification for the action. Reasons may also be specified for not performing an action.

The status of an action. It is expected that the range of values for statusCode (i.e., the value set) will vary by the subtypes of Action. For example, Proposal might have one of its status value as Declined.
The past statuses of this action, e.g., an order may evolve from draft to placed to in progress to completed or canceled.

The source for the context such as the who, what, when, where, how (e.g., origination mode) responsible for proposing, planning, ordering and authorizing, etc... Note that one may also use provenance if provenance information is preferred to be external to the resource.

The FindingContext class aligns with the SNOMED Situations with Explicit Context for findings and provides the context for the topic of a clinical statement. For instance, a statement about findings may state that the finding was observed present or absent. By default, the negation applies to the conjunction of the stated attribute in the instance.

An offer or a suggestion to perform a healthcare act. A recommendation to a provider is an example of proposal made by a CDS system. A proposal must be accepted by an entity in order for it to be performed.
The time when the action is expected to be performed.
Persons who are expected to or intended to perform this action, e.g., the person who will perform the surgery.
Characterizes how quickly the proposed act must be initiated. Includes concepts such as stat, urgent, routine.
Indicates whether the act being proposed should be performed only if needed, i.e., when a certain condition occurs. The condition can be described in the attribute prnReason.
The proposed act must be performed if the indicated conditions occur, e.g.., shortness of breath, SpO2 less than x%, insomnia, nausea.
The actual performance or execution of a healthcare-related action, e.g., 3rd dose of Hepatitis B vaccine administered on Dec 4th 2012, appendectomy performed today.
The overall time period in which the action is performed. This may be different than the scheduled time or the expected performance time.

Persons who perform this action, e.g., the person who administered the medication, performed the surgery.
A performance may have many participants In comparison, an order or a plan typically has one participant. Hence, in performance many participants can be described along with their specific roles.

The component of a composite action that was performed. For instance, the fulfillment of a prescription may result in both a substance administration event and a dispense event, thus resulting in two action being performed.
Identifies a plan that is partly or wholly enacted by the performance of this act
Identifies an order that is partly or wholly filled by the performance of this act
Identifies a proposal that led to this order.
A record that a clinical act was not performed and/or never initiated. Do not use this context if the act was initiated or started but aborted or cancelled. Use the NotPerformed context instead.
The time period during which the act was not performed.
Description of action that is planned to be performed. Typically, this would include a time at which the action is scheduled to be performed.
Identifies an order that is partly or wholly filled by the performance of this act
Identifies a proposal that led to this order.
The time when the action is expected to be performed.
Persons who are expected to or intended to perform this action, e.g., the person who will perform the surgery.
Concept represents a recommendation from a clinical decision support system or advice from a consultation to not perform an act.
The time period during which the act should not be performed.
Normal, abnormal, panic high, panic low, ...
Flag indicating whether there was a significant change from previous results
Flag indicating whether this is a significant result that requires further attention (?)
An instruction by a healthcare provider to another healthcare provider to perform some act.
Time when the ordered act is expected to be performed.
Persons who are expected to or intended to perform this action, e.g., the person who will perform the surgery.
Identifies a proposal that led to this order.
Characterizes how quickly the action must be initiated. Includes concepts such as stat, urgent, routine.
Indicates whether the act being ordered should be performed only if needed, i.e., when a certain condition occurs. The condition can be described in the attribute prnReason.
The ordered act should be performed if the indicated conditions occur, e.g.., shortness of breath, SpO2 less than x%, insomnia, nausea.
A record that a clinical act was initiated by not completed.
Lab result that is pathoneumonic for a disease
This attribute specifies the body site affected by a condition.
This attribute specifies the body site affected by a condition.

This attribute asserts an interaction between two concepts beyond simple co-occurrence in the patient. |ASSOCIATED WITH| represents a clinically relevant association between concepts without either asserting or excluding a causal or sequential relationship between the two.
This attribute identifies the direct causative agent of a disease. It does not include vectors, e.g. a mosquito that transmits malaria.

This attribute is used to relate a |Clinical finding| directly to its cause. If a clinical finding merely predisposes to or worsens another disorder, rather than causing it directly, then the more general attribute | ASSOCIATED WITH | is used instead.

This attribute is used to model concepts in which a clinical finding occurs after another clinical finding or procedure. Neither asserting nor excluding a causal relationship, it instead emphasizes a sequence of events.

This attribute is used to subclass a |Clinical finding| concept according to its severity; however, caution is encouraged because this use is said to be relative. By relative, it is meant that it is incorrect to assume that the same degree of disease intensity or hazard is implied for all |Clinical finding| to which this attribute is applied. There are three reasons. First, severe could be interpreted differently depending on what other values are available to choose for severity.Thus severity is relative to the other values in the value set presented to users. Consider the different meaning of severity in each of the following three sets of values: mild / moderate / severe minimal / mild / moderate / severe / very severe mild / mild to moderate / moderate / moderate to severe / severe / life threatening / fatal Second, the severity is defined relative to the expected degree of intensity or hazard of the |Clinical finding| that is being qualified. A common cold has a baseline intensity or hazard much less than that of a more serious disease like lupus erythematosus or pneumonia; thus a severe cold might be considered less intense or hazardous than a mild pneumonia. Third, some disorders that are life-threatening do not ordinarily have a severity assigned to them. Cancer, for example, is generally not subclassed according to mild, moderate and severe types, but rather is subclassed according to stage or grade.

This attribute is used to represent both the course and onset of a disease. Many conditions with an acute (sudden) onset also have an acute (short duration) course. Few diseases with a chronic (long - term) course would need to have their onset sub-divided into rapid or gradual subtypes, and thus there is no clear need for separating the rapidity of onset from the duration of a disease; based on testing by implementers and modelers, a single attribute with values that combine these meanings has clearly been more reproducible and useful than two attributes that attempt to separate the meanings.

|EPISODICITY| is used to represent episodes of care provided by a physician or other care provider, typically a general practitioner, not episodes of disease experienced by the patient. See EPISODICITY no longer modeled in active content (7.1), regarding the origin of the attribute. For example, asthma with |EPISODICITY|=| first episode | represents the first time the patient presents to their health care provider with asthma. EPISODICITY is not used to model any concepts pre-coordinated in the International Release but it can still be used in post-coordination as a qualifier.

This attribute refers to the entity being evaluated or interpreted, when an evaluation, interpretation or judgment is intrinsic to the meaning of a concept. This attribute is usually grouped with the | HAS INTERPRETATION | attribute.

This attribute provides information about the underlying pathological process for a disorder, but only when the results of that process are not structural and cannot be represented by the |ASSOCIATED MORPHOLOGY| attribute. The values |Infectious process (qualifier value)| and its subtype |Parasitic process (qualifier value)| are included in the range for | PATHOLOGICAL PROCESS |. These were added to accommodate the change in the modeling of concepts in the |Infectious disease (disorder)| subhierarchy where the infectious aspect of the disease is represented using |PATHOLOGICAL PROCESS|.

This attribute provides information about the underlying pathological process for a disorder, but only when the results of that process are not structural and cannot be represented by the |ASSOCIATED MORPHOLOGY| attribute. The values |Infectious process (qualifier value)| and its subtype |Parasitic process (qualifier value)| are included in the range for | PATHOLOGICAL PROCESS |. These were added to accommodate the change in the modeling of concepts in the |Infectious disease (disorder)| subhierarchy where the infectious aspect of the disease is represented using |PATHOLOGICAL PROCESS|.

This attribute specifies the means by which a clinical finding was determined.This attribute is frequently used in conjunction with |FINDING INFORMER|. Findings that specify that they were determined by examination of the patient (e.g. |On examination - ankle clonus (finding)|) should have a value for both |FINDING METHOD| and | FINDING INFORMER |.
The age of the patient or subject at onset of the Condition. Note that this property could potentially be derived.
Set of values bounded by low and high If present, low SHALL have a lower value than high
Date, if known, when clinical finding abated.
Active Relapse Remission Resolved Confirmed, Error?? Ruled out Unknown

The verification status to support or decline the clinical status of the condition or diagnosis. Provisional This is a tentative diagnosis - still a candidate that is under consideration. Differential One of a set of potential (and typically mutually exclusive) diagnosis asserted to further guide the diagnostic process and preliminary treatment. Confirmed There is sufficient diagnostic and/or clinical evidence to treat this as a confirmed condition. Refuted This condition has been ruled out by diagnostic and clinical evidence. entered-in-error Entered In Error The statement was entered in error and is not valid. Unknown The condition status is unknown. Note that "unknown" is a value of last resort and every attempt should be made to provide a meaningful value other than "unknown".
Date and time the health problem was diagnosed. Added for Public Health Reporting Initiative, 10/5/2012.
Incubation period (exposed, asymptomatic) Prodromal (symptoms but not full disease breakout) Acute (full manifestation of disease) Convalescent

AssociatedPrecondition describes the previously existing conditions or states that could effect a measurement or assesment. For example; a patients weight taken while clothed, a patients height with or without shoes, a patients blood pressure taken while standing or lying down.

AssociatedSignAndSymptom is a component which captures the accompanying physical observations captured by a clinician or subjective conditions experienced by a patient that are related to a medical condition.
AlleviatingFactor this CEM model captures the action or intervention which makes a symptom less prevalent. Examples of data from the value set may include: rest, heat, ice, etc.

ExacerbatingFactor model is a component model. This model holds a question in the code and holds a coded value (CD) answer from the value set referred to in data. For example, in the ExacerbatingFactor model the question is What is the exacerbating factor? and the coded answer from the ExacerbatingFactor VALUESET set can be activity, etc. ExacerbatingFactor by definition means an action, object, or something that makes a condition or problem worse.
Periodicity, the length of time from one occurrence to the next (e.g., intermittent, weekly, continuous).

project:Project.description:
The Reference Model Profile (RMP) enables the specification of reference models, upon which archetypes can be based.  The RMP enables the identification of a root package that identifies the set of reference model elements (REM) that can be constrained by a collection of archetype model elements (AME) in an Archetype Library.

 

The RMP provides the ability to associate the "primitive data types" identified in an instance of a Constraint Model Profile with the corresponding (mapped) data types in the reference model.  It also allows properties in the target reference model to be identified as "unconstrainable", because they carry "runtime" provenance and workflow information or because they carry "infrastructure" items such as archetype identifiers, etc.
